<h2>Chapter 4: The Split Between Traditional SEO and AI Search Optimization</h2>
<p>SEO is splitting into two distinct disciplines. Mike King, CEO of iPullRank, called this out directly: treating traditional SEO and AI search optimization as <a href="https://searchengineland.com/ai-search-visibility-seo-predictions-2026-468042">the same strategic problem is a mistake</a>.</p>
<h3>Traditional SEO: Still Necessary</h3>
<p>Traditional SEO drives clicks from humans who browse, compare, and buy. These searchers want to visit websites. They click through product pages, read reviews, and fill out forms.</p>
<p>For commercial and transactional queries, traditional SEO remains the primary driver. AI Overviews appear on only <a href="https://heroicrankings.com/seo/managed/google-ai-overview-statistics-2026/">7% of local searches</a> and have limited presence in product comparison queries.</p>
<p>The fundamentals still matter. <a href="/blog/on-page-seo-guide/">On-page SEO</a>, <a href="/blog/how-to-do-seo-audit/">technical site health</a>, <a href="/blog/internal-linking-blog-posts/">internal linking</a>, and <a href="/blog/build-topical-authority/">topical authority</a> continue to drive organic rankings.</p>
<h3>AI Search Optimization: The New Discipline</h3>
<p>AI search optimization focuses on making your content machine-readable, citable, and authoritative enough for AI engines to reference.</p>
<p>This is closer to what the industry calls <a href="/blog/generative-engine-optimization-guide/">Generative Engine Optimization (GEO)</a>. It requires different tactics.</p>
